and":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England","Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"D'Arques","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Mario, Luis, Fernando, Jorge, Armando, Ana, Joaquin, Julio, Marcos.  Portuguese Joao, Joaquim, Paulo, Henrique, Lourenco, Seraphine, Vasco.","Catalan (<b>Marquès</b>); Spanish and southern French (<b>Marqués</b>): from Catalan <i>marquès</i>, Spanish and Occitan <i>marqués</i> ‘marquis’, words of French origin (see   Marquis  ), applied either as a nickname for someone who behaved like a marquis or as an occupational name for a servant in the household of a marquis.","Portuguese: patronymic from the personal name   Marcos  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marquis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Normand, Marcel, Fernand, Lucien, Rosaire, Andre, Armand, Camille, Cecile, Jacques, Francois.","French: from the title <i>marquis</i> ‘marquess’, applied as an ironic nickname to someone who behaved like a marquis or as a metonymic occupational name for a servant in the household of a marquis. The title, derived from an ancient Germanic word meaning ‘boundary’ (compare   March  ), originally referred to the governor of a border territory. Marquises did not form part of the original French feudal structure of nobility; the title was first adopted by the Counts of Toulouse because of their possessions in the border region beyond the Rhône. Compare   Markee   and   Markey  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>markis</i> ‘marquis, marquess, nobleman’ (Old French <i>marchis</i>); see also 1 above. The word is also found as a female personal name which may also be origin of the surname."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705179,"age":9,"year":"1013","julianDay":2091051,"title":"Sweyn Forkbeard","description":"The Danes raided and captured England. Sweyn, King of Danes, was declared King of England on Christmas Day.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweyn_Forkbeard","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Sweyn Forkbeard","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705180,"age":12,"year":"1016","julianDay":2092146,"title":"Canut the Great","description":"As Aethelred, King of England died, his son, Edmund Ironside devised a truce with Danish King Canute. The truce divided the kingdom between the two but Edmund died shortly after and became King of England. Several years later, he also became king of Denmark.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cnut_the_Great","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Cnut the Great","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705181,"age":31,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Havisia D'Arques was born in 1004, in Normandy, France. She had at least 1 son with Osbern Giffard d'Arques, Seigneur de Brimesfelde. She died in 1080, in Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1004–1080":"1004–1080","0985–1090":"0985–1090","1044–1096":"1044–1096","1080":"1080","0985":"0985","1090":"1090","1016":"1016","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1044":"1044","1096":"1096","about 1044":"umbes 1044","Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England","Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1004–1080":"1004–1080","0985–1090":"0985–1090","1044–1096":"1044–1096","1080":"1080","0985":"0985","1090":"1090","1016":"1016","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1044":"1044","1096":"1096","about 1044":"noin 1044","Brimpsfield, Gloucestersh